<!--
  025. PII Handling Template

  Personally Identifiable Information (PII) requires special handling in LLM applications.
  This template demonstrates patterns for:
  - Pre-processing redaction (safest approach)
  - Output constraints (when pre-redaction isn't possible)
  - Extraction with selective redaction
  - Handling uncertain/ambiguous PII

  Key principle: Defense in depth. Never rely solely on prompt constraints.
  Combine with pre-processing detection, post-processing validation, and logging policies.
-->

<prompt>
  <!--
    ============================================================================
    PII CATEGORIES REFERENCE
    ============================================================================
    Define what constitutes PII for your use case. This varies by jurisdiction
    (GDPR, CCPA, HIPAA) and context.
  -->
  <pii_categories>
    <!-- Direct Identifiers - Always PII -->
    <category id="name" sensitivity="high">Full names, first/last names</category>
    <category id="email" sensitivity="high">Email addresses</category>
    <category id="phone" sensitivity="high">Phone numbers (any format)</category>
    <category id="ssn" sensitivity="critical">Social Security Numbers, Tax IDs</category>
    <category id="financial" sensitivity="critical">Credit card numbers, bank accounts</category>
    <category id="address" sensitivity="high">Physical addresses, ZIP codes (when combined)</category>
    <category id="id_numbers" sensitivity="high">Driver's license, passport, employee IDs</category>

    <!-- Quasi-Identifiers - PII in combination -->
    <category id="dob" sensitivity="medium">Date of birth</category>
    <category id="age" sensitivity="low">Age (PII when combined with other data)</category>
    <category id="gender" sensitivity="low">Gender/sex</category>
    <category id="location" sensitivity="medium">City, state (PII when combined)</category>
    <category id="employer" sensitivity="medium">Employer name, job title</category>

    <!-- Sensitive but not always PII -->
    <category id="health" sensitivity="high">Medical conditions, medications (HIPAA)</category>
    <category id="biometric" sensitivity="critical">Fingerprints, facial recognition data</category>
    <category id="behavioral" sensitivity="medium">Purchase history, browsing patterns</category>
  </pii_categories>

  <!--
    ============================================================================
    PATTERN 1: PRE-PROCESSING REDACTION
    ============================================================================
    The safest approach: redact PII before it reaches the model.
    Use consistent placeholder formats that preserve semantic meaning.
  -->
  <redaction_format>
    <!--
      Placeholder convention: [TYPE_N] where N is a counter
      This preserves referential identity (same person = same placeholder)
      without revealing actual values.
    -->
    <placeholder type="name">[PERSON_N]</placeholder>
    <placeholder type="email">[EMAIL_N]</placeholder>
    <placeholder type="phone">[PHONE_N]</placeholder>
    <placeholder type="address">[ADDRESS_N]</placeholder>
    <placeholder type="ssn">[SSN_REDACTED]</placeholder>
    <placeholder type="account">[ACCOUNT_N]</placeholder>
    <placeholder type="date_of_birth">[DOB_REDACTED]</placeholder>
    <placeholder type="credit_card">[CC_REDACTED]</placeholder>

    <!--
      Example of redacted input:

      Original:
        "Hi, I'm John Smith (john.smith@email.com). My account #12345
         was charged twice. Please call me at 555-123-4567."

      Redacted:
        "Hi, I'm [PERSON_1] ([EMAIL_1]). My account [ACCOUNT_1]
         was charged twice. Please call me at [PHONE_1]."
    -->
  </redaction_format>

  <!--
    ============================================================================
    PATTERN 2: OUTPUT CONSTRAINTS
    ============================================================================
    When pre-redaction isn't possible, constrain outputs explicitly.
  -->
  <pii_constraints>
    <!-- Critical: These must never be violated -->
    <constraint priority="critical" id="PII-001">
      Never output: full names, email addresses, phone numbers, physical addresses,
      SSNs, account numbers, credit card numbers, or other direct identifiers.
    </constraint>
    <constraint priority="critical" id="PII-002">
      When referencing individuals, use generic terms: "the customer", "the user",
      "the applicant", "Person A/B/C" - never actual names.
    </constraint>
    <constraint priority="critical" id="PII-003">
      If the task requires acknowledging contact information exists, state the type
      only: "email address provided" not the actual address.
    </constraint>

    <!-- High: Should not be violated without explicit override -->
    <constraint priority="high" id="PII-004">
      Do not output combinations of quasi-identifiers that could identify someone:
      e.g., "45-year-old female accountant in Springfield" is identifying.
    </constraint>
    <constraint priority="high" id="PII-005">
      Do not quote text that contains PII. Paraphrase instead, replacing
      identifiers with generic references.
    </constraint>

    <!-- Standard: Follow unless task specifically requires otherwise -->
    <constraint priority="standard" id="PII-006">
      Round ages to decades ("in their 40s") rather than exact ages.
    </constraint>
    <constraint priority="standard" id="PII-007">
      Use region-level locations ("Midwest US") rather than specific cities
      unless geographic precision is essential to the task.
    </constraint>
  </pii_constraints>

  <!--
    ============================================================================
    PATTERN 3: HANDLING UNCERTAINTY
    ============================================================================
    When it's unclear whether data is PII, err on the side of privacy.
  -->
  <uncertainty_handling>
    <policy id="default">
      When uncertain whether data constitutes PII, treat it as PII.
      False positives (over-redaction) are preferable to false negatives (PII leakage).
    </policy>

    <policy id="ambiguous_names">
      Words that could be names or common nouns (e.g., "Rose", "Hunter", "Chase"):
      - In direct address or signature context: treat as name (PII)
      - As standalone words: treat as non-PII
      - When uncertain: treat as PII
    </policy>

    <policy id="numbers">
      Strings of digits that could be identifiers:
      - 9 digits: assume SSN (critical PII)
      - 10 digits: assume phone number (high PII)
      - 16 digits: assume credit card (critical PII)
      - Other lengths: flag for review, default to redaction
    </policy>

    <policy id="context_dependent">
      Some data is PII only in context:
      - "John" alone: possibly not PII
      - "John, the project manager at Acme Corp": PII (identifiable)
      Flag such contextual combinations for review.
    </policy>
  </uncertainty_handling>

  <!--
    ============================================================================
    SELF-CHECKS
    ============================================================================
  -->
  <checks>
    <check id="CHK-PII-001">Scan output for email patterns (contains @)</check>
    <check id="CHK-PII-002">Scan output for phone patterns (7+ consecutive digits, formatted numbers)</check>
    <check id="CHK-PII-003">Scan output for potential names (capitalized words in person-reference context)</check>
    <check id="CHK-PII-004">Verify no direct quotes from input that contain identifiers</check>
    <check id="CHK-PII-005">Check that any placeholder from input is used verbatim, not "decoded"</check>
  </checks>

  <!--
    ============================================================================
    AUDIT LOGGING STRUCTURE
    ============================================================================
    Log PII handling decisions without logging the PII itself.
  -->
  <audit_log_schema>
    <![CDATA[
{
  "timestamp": "ISO8601",
  "prompt_id": "string",
  "prompt_version": "string",
  "pii_handling": {
    "approach": "pre-redacted | output-constrained | hybrid",
    "redaction_applied": true | false,
    "redaction_counts": {
      "names": 0,
      "emails": 0,
      "phones": 0,
      "addresses": 0,
      "other": 0
    },
    "constraints_applied": ["PII-001", "PII-002", ...],
    "uncertainty_flags": [
      {
        "type": "ambiguous_name",
        "action_taken": "redacted",
        "confidence": 0.7
      }
    ]
  },
  "output_validation": {
    "pii_scan_passed": true | false,
    "patterns_detected": []
  }
}
    ]]>
  </audit_log_schema>
</prompt>

<!--
  ============================================================================
  IMPLEMENTATION NOTES
  ============================================================================

  1. DEFENSE IN DEPTH
     Never rely solely on prompt constraints for PII protection.
     Layer your defenses:

     Layer 1: Input sanitization (pre-processing)
       - Run PII detection before sending to model
       - Use named entity recognition (NER) for names
       - Use regex patterns for structured PII (emails, phones, SSNs)
       - Replace detected PII with placeholders

     Layer 2: Prompt constraints (this template)
       - Explicit instructions not to output PII
       - Self-check requirements
       - Generic reference requirements

     Layer 3: Output validation (post-processing)
       - Scan model output for PII patterns
       - Block or redact before returning to user
       - Log violations for review

     Layer 4: Logging policies
       - Never log raw inputs containing PII
       - Log redacted versions only
       - Store PII mapping separately with encryption

  2. REGULATORY CONSIDERATIONS

     GDPR (EU):
       - Broad definition of personal data
       - Includes IP addresses, cookie IDs
       - Requires explicit consent for processing
       - Right to erasure implications

     CCPA (California):
       - Includes household data
       - Requires disclosure of data categories
       - Opt-out rights for data sales

     HIPAA (US Healthcare):
       - 18 specific identifiers
       - Includes dates, geographic data
       - Requires de-identification standards

     Customize pii_categories based on applicable regulations.

  3. TESTING STRATEGY

     Include these test cases:
     - Obvious PII: "john.doe@email.com" should never appear in output
     - Subtle PII: Birthdate + ZIP code combination
     - Contextual PII: Common word that becomes a name in context
     - Adversarial: Input asking model to "repeat my email"
     - Edge cases: International formats (non-US phones, EU postal codes)

  4. PLACEHOLDER REVERSIBILITY

     If you need to restore PII after processing (e.g., for personalized responses):
     - Store placeholder mappings in secure, encrypted storage
     - Apply strict access controls to mapping data
     - Restore PII only at the final output stage, after all logging
     - Never send restored PII back through the model
-->
